g.text: Uber is a ride-sharing platforms that connect passengers with drivers who offer transportation services
in personal vehicles. It allows users to book rides on-demand from their smartphones, matching them
with a nearby driver who will take them from their location to their desired destination.
1. Users should be able to input a start location and a destination and get an estimate fare
2. User should be able to request a ride based on an estimate
3. Drivers should be able to accept/deny a request and navigate to pickup/drop-off
- low latency matching < 1 min to match or failure
- consistency of matching. Ride to driver is 1:1
- handle high throughout, surges for peak hours or special events. 100s of thousands of requests within a given region
Hierarchical structure is efficient for spatial data indexing, supporting fast retrieval.
Well-suited for bounding box searches and spatial queries.
Precision is consistent across the map.
More complex implementation than Geohash, with potentially higher computational overhead.
Requires more space for storage due to the structure and pointers.
Not as straightforward for sharing location data as compared to a single string representation.
Simple representation as a single string, making it easy to store and share.
Efficient for proximity searches, as nearby locations often share a prefix.
Precision varies across latitudes; higher latitudes have less precision.
Not as efficient for bounding box searches due to its Z-order curve properties.
Boundary issue: adjacent areas may not share the same prefix, complicating proximity searches.
1. We don't send more than one request at a time for a given ride
2. We don't send any driver more than one request at a time.
